\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating serialization methods**\\n\\nI'm considering whether I can avoid using a custom object stream and questioning why it was employed in a private test. It seems the Native Image agent may not record `readObject` for plain `byte[]`. The current setup involves `ObjectOutputStream.writeObject(this.getEncoded())`, which might be unnecessarily complicated by the inclusion of extra serialization metadata. I wonder if the existing private customizations are there to ensure proper handling during deserialization. However, `ObjectInputStream` can manage `byte[]` without needing the extra metadata. How intriguing!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating deserialization process**\\n\\nI'm analyzing a call inside `readObject` to `ObjectInputStream#readObject`. If the `byte[]` object was replaced by `BCDSTU4145PublicKeyEncodedKey`, it seems that it would return a resolved `byte[]` but require the `readResolve` method to be invoked reflectively, which might need metadata for the test class. Native tests might include all classes through reflection, which could lead to failures if things aren't handled correctly. I wonder if we need to add `Security.addProvider`, though no algorithm is being used. It feels like a complex scenario!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering KeyFactory alternatives**\\n\\nI'm realizing that the existing use of the KeyFactory public API seems more internal, and since it failed in the native environment, I wonder if using the JCA KeyFactory could work if I add provider services during the build process. However, it looks like the native setup lacks algorithms because dynamic class loading is unsupported, and this may lead to missing metadata. It feels tricky, and I want to avoid complications with the metadata!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Checking test modifications**\\n\\nI need to see if the active class in the native test failed after the modifications I made. It's a good idea to check this. I’m wondering if I also need to adjust BCDSTU4145PrivateKey, but it seems like it only applies to inactive cases. Maybe I should update the test method name as well; that seems fine. Let’s ensure everything is set for the next steps!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Refined the active-class test:\n\n- Updated `tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15to18/1.77/src/test/java/org_bouncycastle/bcprov_jdk15to18/BCDSTU4145PublicKeyTest.java`\n\nChange made:\n- Replaced `KeyFactory.getInstance(\"DSTU4145\", new BouncyCastleProvider())` generation with direct construction of `BCDSTU4145PublicKey` using Bouncy Castle’s public key spec and provider configuration.\n\nReason:\n- The previous path could fail under Native Image before reaching serialization because the `DSTU4145` provider service was not available.\n- The revised path avoids provider algorithm lookup and should allow the test to reach:\n  - `BCDSTU4145PublicKey.writeObject(...)`\n  - `BCDSTU4145PublicKey.readObject(...)`\n\nPer instruction, I did not run tests locally.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_03a86127b9e34355016a25bdce1754819481263adfe96bfa0d\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1811, "output": 1353, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32348, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1780858287303, "responseId": "resp_03a86127b9e34355016a25bdafbd4081949d607a118ad7e42d"}, "toolResults": []}
